WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.540
&gt;&gt; Jon Parrish Peede:
Good morning.

00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:04.450
And welcome to the
18th annual Library

00:00:04.450 --> 00:00:07.230
of Congress National
Book Festival.

00:00:07.230 --> 00:00:09.750
I'm Jon Parrish Peede,
I'm the chairman

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:12.400
of the National Endowment
for the Humanities.

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:15.910
And NEH is proud to sponsor
this year's Understanding Our

00:00:15.910 --> 00:00:17.350
World stage.

00:00:17.350 --> 00:00:23.650
An independent federal agency,
NEH was established in 1965

00:00:23.650 --> 00:00:27.560
under LBJ as part of the
great society legislation.

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:32.450
And we're rooted with our sister
agency NEA, still in that cause.

00:00:32.450 --> 00:00:36.280
Our agency supports museum
exhibitions, documentaries,

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:39.960
books that bring history,
literature, philosophy,

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:44.000
archaeology, and the other
humanities fields to the public.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.470
We fund the preservation

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:48.640
of historic records,
collections, objects.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:52.640
We sponsor the educational
opportunities for K12 teachers

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:56.420
across this nation and for
students in the humanities.

00:00:56.420 --> 00:01:00.120
And we underride fundamental
research across the disciplines

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:02.620
of the humanities
at universities

00:01:02.620 --> 00:01:05.630
and for independent
scholars across this nation.

00:01:05.630 --> 00:01:09.550
And so it is my absolute
pleasure to be here

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:13.060
to introduce this panel,
Monumental Decisions,

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:17.060
which will be led by four
scholars for thinkers

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:19.610
and writers and their
book signings will be

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:24.690
on the lower level shortly
after this program at 11.30.

00:01:24.690 --> 00:01:29.600
In terms of NEH, we have always
taken an interest in memorials.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:33.560
I can say, for example,
in 1979, the same year

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:37.000
that the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial Fund was created,

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.060
NEH issued a grant for
a national symposium

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:44.810
on issues raised by the memorial
and plans for an archive

00:01:44.810 --> 00:01:48.800
of the soldiers'
experiences in Southeast Asia.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.080
Our four guests have devoted
so much time and research

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:56.510
and wisdom to contemplating
the complexity

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:00.450
of who gets remembered
in wars and why.

00:02:00.450 --> 00:02:05.150
And how the narrative of war
changes in response over time.

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:09.320
So our panelists include
professor Kristin Hass,

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:12.950
James Reston Jr,
Professor Kirk Savage,

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:15.500
and our moderator
is Brent D. Glass.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:17.580
Of course, many of us
in Washington know him

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:18.940
as director emeritus

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:22.940
of the Smithsonian's National
Museum of American History.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.330
He's a public scholar.

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:28.040
He particularly advanced the
area of oral scholarship,

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.200
oral histories, and
oral narratives.

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:33.200
He's a national leader
in the preservation

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:35.120
and interpretation of history.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:38.980
Glass also served as
a member for a decade

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:42.610
of the Flight 93 Memorial
Advisory Commission.

00:02:42.610 --> 00:02:46.090
He is the author of "50
Great American Places,

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:49.910
Essential Historic
Sites Across the US."

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:53.270
Brent will introduce our
panelists, so please join me

00:02:53.270 --> 00:02:56.510
in giving them a warm welcome.

00:02:56.510 --> 00:03:02.070
[ Applause ]

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:05.330
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Thank
you, Chairman Peede.

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:07.090
And welcome everyone.

00:03:07.090 --> 00:03:10.870
It's a delight for me
to share this panel.

00:03:10.870 --> 00:03:13.440
And I do want to recognize
the National Endowment

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:17.040
for the Humanities and the
outstanding support they give

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:20.310
to scholarship in the
humanities for many, many years.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:24.540
And all of us on this panel I
believe have benefited and many

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:26.080
of us in the audience
have benefited

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:27.430
for the support from NEH.

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:31.900
So it's a real honor to chair
this panel sponsored by NEH.

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:41.320
We, the subject of statues
and monuments and memorials

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.170
of course is not a new issue.

00:03:44.170 --> 00:03:49.150
But I think not since the time
of Licinius, in the 4th century,

00:03:49.150 --> 00:03:53.810
Licinius tore down some statues
of the emperor Constantine

00:03:53.810 --> 00:03:57.560
and triggered a civil war, not
since that time has there been

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:00.360
so much contention
and discussion

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:02.370
about statues and memorials.

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:08.180
And our panelists today are very
well prepared to talk about it.

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:11.330
But with such a good audience
and an engaged audience,

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:14.010
we've left time at the
end of this session

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:15.310
for you to participate.

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:20.950
So it's very important that
we have your reaction to some

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:25.590
of the issues that will be
raised here this morning.

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:29.210
So Kristin Hass is the associate
professor in the department

00:04:29.210 --> 00:04:33.260
of American culture and director
of the Humanities Collaboratory

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:35.600
at the University of Michigan.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:38.250
She has written two books,
"Sacrificing Soldiers

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:43.500
on the National Mall; A Study of
Militarism, Race, War Memorials,

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:47.170
and US Nationalism," and
the other book is "Carried

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:51.950
to the Wall; American Memory and
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial;

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:55.350
an Exploration of Playback
Memorial Practices,

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:57.290
Material Culture Studies,

00:04:57.290 --> 00:05:00.440
and the Legacies of
the Vietnam War."

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:04.720
Kirk Savage is the Dietrich
professor of History, Art,

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:07.980
and Architecture at the
University of Pittsburgh.

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:11.820
He is the editor of "The
Civil War in Art and Memory,"

00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:15.340
the author of two books,
"Standing Soldiers,

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:18.840
Kneeling Slaves; Race,
War, and Monument

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:21.430
in 19th Century America,"
which is just

00:05:21.430 --> 00:05:25.740
out from Princeton University
Press in its second edition,

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:29.130
and also "Monument
Wars; Washington DC,

00:05:29.130 --> 00:05:31.360
the National Mall,
and the Transformation

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:33.950
of the Memorial Landscape."

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:38.400
James Reston Jr is the author
of 18 books, including "Warriors

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:41.200
of God" and "The
Conviction of Richard Nixon,"

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:45.240
which inspired the play
turned film "Frost/Nixon."

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:48.440
He has also written three
plays, numerous articles

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.810
in national magazines, and
an award winning documentary

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:55.710
about the 1978 Jonestown
massacre.

00:05:55.710 --> 00:05:58.450
His last five historical
works have been translated

00:05:58.450 --> 00:06:00.960
into 13 languages.

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:03.490
"Warriors of God" is an
international bestseller

00:06:03.490 --> 00:06:08.370
with over 200,000 copies
sold and still selling.

00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:11.680
Which I think is
always good news.

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:14.370
"Fragile Innocence,"
another one of his books,

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:17.700
is a memoir of bringing up
his handicapped daughter.

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:19.170
And it reached number eight

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:21.520
on the Washington
Post bestseller list.

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:25.900
His new book is "A Rift
in the Earth; Art, Memory,

00:06:25.900 --> 00:06:29.300
and the Fight for a
Vietnam War Memorial."

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:31.510
So please welcome our panel.

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:38.180
[ Applause ]

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:40.200
And what we're going to
do is this is divided

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:41.680
into really four parts.

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:43.920
First, I've asked our
panel to talk a little bit

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:47.530
about the intellectual path that
led them to write their books

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:50.080
on monuments and memorials.

00:06:50.080 --> 00:06:55.270
Second, we will talk about their
thoughts concerning memorials

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:59.850
on the National Mall, especially
those that have been inspired

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:03.630
by the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial, but memorials

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:05.930
that have appeared
around the country

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:11.110
since the Veterans War
Memorial has been dedicated.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:13.580
And then the third part of
our panel will be to talk

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:17.220
about making monuments and
what we should be thinking

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:18.710
about about the monuments

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:22.340
that were dedicated
more than 100 years ago.

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:25.610
As a result of the
commemoration of the Civil War.

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:27.280
And finally will be your turn

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:30.310
to ask us questions
or make comments.

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:34.070
So just leading off, I will
just mention briefly why I came

00:07:34.070 --> 00:07:36.400
to write "50 Great
American Places."

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:39.530
And David McCullough, who wrote
the forward to the book said

00:07:39.530 --> 00:07:41.990
to me "Write the book that
you would want to read."

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:45.160
And the book I wanted
to read had three goals.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:48.830
One was to inspire
history education.

00:07:48.830 --> 00:07:51.380
Second was to encourage
people to go out

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:53.870
and visit historic places.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:57.560
And the third goal was to
encourage the preservation

00:07:57.560 --> 00:07:59.120
of our historic sites.

00:07:59.120 --> 00:08:02.790
Now several other sites that
I write about are also related

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:05.650
to the memorial landscape
of America.

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:09.820
There's the USS Arizona
and Pearl Harbor,

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:13.790
the Salem Witch Trial memorial
in Salem, Massachusetts,

00:08:13.790 --> 00:08:17.650
of course the National Mall,
the Memorial at Wounded Knee,

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:20.650
South Dakota, and also
the Statue of Liberty.

00:08:20.650 --> 00:08:23.770
And I may have a few comments to
make about the Statue of Liberty

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:25.170
because it's a great
illustration

00:08:25.170 --> 00:08:28.940
of how some memorials wind up
in the public consciousness

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:31.720
in a very different
way, have us thinking

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:34.170
in a very different
way, than how,

00:08:34.170 --> 00:08:36.690
what they were originally
conceived to be.

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:42.750
But I want to stop and let our
panel discuss the intellectual

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:47.790
biography of the books, how they
came to write what they wrote

00:08:47.790 --> 00:08:49.570
about memorials and monuments.

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:52.140
And Kristin Hass, would
you please lead off.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:54.150
&gt;&gt; Kristin Ann Hass:
I'd be happy to.

00:08:54.150 --> 00:08:57.210
Good morning.

00:08:57.210 --> 00:09:04.320
I started with an
interest in patriotism

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:11.030
in how patriotism works, in
where that you hear the anthem

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:14.100
and you get a hit of emotion.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:20.440
I was really interested in how
that came to be, who made it.

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:26.810
I was a hippie kid from northern
California and understood myself

00:09:26.810 --> 00:09:29.770
to be intensely patriotic.

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:34.700
And I was, as a young girl,
fascinated by the First Ladies,

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.370
which for my demographic
was fairly unusual.

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:40.370
And I wasn't interested in
the First Ladies' dresses,

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:45.460
I was interested in for women
who couldn't have access

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:50.770
to the highest office, what it
was like to stand next to that.

00:09:50.770 --> 00:09:54.560
I was interested in emotional,

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:59.240
the emotional power
of patriotism.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:04.530
And that led me to an
interest in public history.

00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:06.720
Who gets to make public history?

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:10.500
What are the stories we tell
each other and ourselves

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:14.330
about who we are and
how we came to be?

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:18.900
And that interest in public
history led me after I graduated

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:21.410
from college to an
unpaid internship

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:24.140
at the National Museum
of American History.

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:27.070
And my first job there
was to work on an exhibit

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:30.050
on everyday life in
the 20th century.

00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:34.320
What are the objects that would
tell the story of American life

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:38.080
in the 20th century to the
millions of middle schoolers

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:41.590
who move through that building?

00:10:41.590 --> 00:10:46.460
The dress that Elizabeth
Eckford wore

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:50.310
on that famous day
in Little Rock.

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:54.260
I was, so I was spending all
my time thinking about kind

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.400
of what are the objects
that tell our story?

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:58.960
Because it was an unpaid
internship, I was a nanny.

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:02.060
And I had an hour
to myself every day.

00:11:02.060 --> 00:11:05.070
So I was running around the Mall
and running around the Mall.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:11.170
I went by the Vietnam Memorial,
first time noticing the objects,

00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:18.090
the boots, the flags, the
flowers, the unexpected toys,

00:11:18.090 --> 00:11:21.830
second time thinking
"What is this?"

00:11:21.830 --> 00:11:24.810
Third time stopping in
my tracks and saying

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:30.770
"This is an incredible
expression of patriotism,"

00:11:30.770 --> 00:11:36.300
but also a making of public
history that was unsolicited,

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:39.400
that was, at that time,
now there's a tragedy

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:42.240
and everybody brings their
stuff, that did not happen

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:44.080
in the United States,
it's ubiquitous now,

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:46.930
it didn't happen before the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial.

00:11:46.930 --> 00:11:51.810
So I brought my interests
in the emotion of patriotism

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:54.180
and the mechanics of patriotism

00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:58.290
and how public history
more broadly is made

00:11:58.290 --> 00:12:00.360
to a study of those objects.

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:03.000
And that's the produced
my description,

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.090
and then my first book
"Carried to the Wall."

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:08.280
And I wrote about
why that mattered.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:10.030
And the second book
is a follow-up.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:13.760
I was interested in
the objects still,

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:17.810
but I was really interested
in how the Vietnam Memorial,

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:20.020
the objects, the place itself,

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:24.200
transformed memorial
practices going forward.

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:25.580
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Thank you.

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:27.230
Jim Reston.

00:12:27.230 --> 00:12:30.080
"Rift in the Land."

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:32.490
&gt;&gt; James Reston Jr: So
I'm a veteran that was

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:36.500
in the Army from 1965 to 1968.

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:42.060
Fortunately only by
happenstance, not in Vietnam.

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:46.610
And afterwards, I became very
involved in the Amnesty Movement

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:51.420
for the return of war
resistors to the United States

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:54.700
who had gone into exile.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:56.820
And the first, the service

00:12:56.820 --> 00:13:00.920
in the Army gave me a
very deep understanding

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:04.310
and sympathy for the soldier.

00:13:04.310 --> 00:13:08.120
Especially the soldier
who is at risk.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:13.580
And the experience with amnesty
gave me a very deep interest

00:13:13.580 --> 00:13:16.520
in the whole question
of reconciliation.

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:20.690
But particularly reconciliation
after a divisive war.

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:23.260
Of course, I was
focused with amnesty

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:28.250
on reconciliation after Vietnam.

00:13:28.250 --> 00:13:33.790
But the historical parallel
of the post-Civil War period

00:13:33.790 --> 00:13:36.790
with its amnesties
were southern soldiers

00:13:36.790 --> 00:13:39.670
and southern leaders,
was a real parallel.

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.550
And the real argument
for a universal amnesty

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:46.330
for Vietnam war resistors.

00:13:46.330 --> 00:13:50.340
So in a way with this current
book, I was returning to some

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:53.300
of those old emotional roots.

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:58.310
I always think that beyond
intellectual interest

00:13:58.310 --> 00:14:00.860
in a subject, it's
a very good thing

00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:03.680
to have an emotional
connection to it.

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:08.290
And in this case, there
were two emotional roots.

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:13.150
One was that I was a good
friend of Frederick Hart,

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:16.970
who is the sculptor
of the three soldiers

00:14:16.970 --> 00:14:20.190
at the Vietnam Memorial.

00:14:20.190 --> 00:14:25.780
The sculptures probably
saved the building

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:29.490
of a Vietnam Memorial
at all, as controversial

00:14:29.490 --> 00:14:31.340
as they are artistically.

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:36.920
So I was very interested in
my interchanges with Rick Hart

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:39.640
about the battle over
the Vietnam Memorial.

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:45.180
The second is that I
have one colleague,

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:48.440
fellow GI, who's on the wall.

00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:56.000
Who was killed in Hue,
Vietnam, January 30th, 1968.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:01.110
As the north Vietnamese came
in invading the city of Hue.

00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:08.880
And so in a way, I personally
experienced the very heart

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:15.010
and the very essence of the
Vietnam Wall of Maya Lin

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:19.040
that the survivors of
Vietnam look at their friends

00:15:19.040 --> 00:15:25.860
who are lost and see their own
image reflected in that wall.

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:29.390
It was the third
impulse, not so noble,

00:15:29.390 --> 00:15:34.840
that my daughter may have
finished her master's degree

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:37.580
at Dartmouth in Vietnam studies.

00:15:37.580 --> 00:15:44.260
And I went to her graduation
ceremony and we had a chance

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:47.300
to talk to her advisor,
who was an advisor

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:50.330
to Ken Burns' Vietnam,

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:54.850
magnificent Vietnam
documentary series.

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:57.880
And this was some time ago.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:03.780
And I asked this scholar when
is the Ken Burns thing going

