00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:52.940
&gt;&gt; Kirk Savage: Okay so
I'm kind of a scholar,

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:54.730
a one-note scholar,
I've been writing

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:58.800
about public monuments
for over 30 years.

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:00.780
I got interested in them

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:04.700
as a college student
in Westminster Abby.

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:07.160
I was fortunate to
study in London.

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:11.360
And seeing these incredible
sort of public tomb monuments

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:14.370
to these figures and trying to
understand why they were erected

00:17:14.370 --> 00:17:15.670
and what they were doing.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:19.720
So I really came in through
the art history side of things.

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:23.810
But when the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial was being erected,

00:17:23.810 --> 00:17:28.210
I just became fascinated with
the controversy surrounding it.

00:17:28.210 --> 00:17:31.810
You know, I too grew up
in the Vietnam War Era.

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:35.390
So I had a lot of ties with,
my parents were involved

00:17:35.390 --> 00:17:37.350
with the anti-war movement.

00:17:37.350 --> 00:17:42.630
But the controversy itself
was what really engaged me.

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:47.390
How was it that formal design
questions could suddenly become

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:50.250
so emotionally significant?

00:17:50.250 --> 00:17:53.050
So politically significant
to people?

00:17:53.050 --> 00:17:56.330
And really trying to understand
the how and why of that.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:17:59.110
So it was kind of the perfect
marriage of art and politics,

00:17:59.110 --> 00:18:03.240
which were really my two,
my two key interests.

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:05.950
And so that's how I got into
actually starting to write

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:07.250
about public monuments.

00:18:07.250 --> 00:18:11.020
And then from there, I realized
the Washington monument,

00:18:11.020 --> 00:18:15.530
in the 19th century, was kind of
the mother of all controversies.

00:18:15.530 --> 00:18:17.260
And I began writing on that

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:22.960
and that propelled my
interest in the National Mall.

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:27.540
Subsequent to that, I got the
idea of writing a dissertation

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:29.830
on Civil War memorials,
which people

00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:33.390
in art history thought was
an absolutely ridiculous idea

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:36.280
because you know, they were
artistically insignificant

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:37.580
and so on, so forth.

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:40.820
That, for me again, it
was all about why were

00:18:40.820 --> 00:18:45.880
so many monuments erected,
and you know, from both sides

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:48.240
in the war and what was their
function, their purpose,

00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:51.780
and why were people so invested
in them became the questions

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:53.710
that I got interested in.

00:18:53.710 --> 00:18:58.720
It was only through that process
of doing my research that more

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:02.630
and more and more I
became really, became more

00:19:02.630 --> 00:19:05.980
and more aware of the importance
of the story of slavery

00:19:05.980 --> 00:19:11.120
and emancipation in the
erection of Civil War memorials.

00:19:11.120 --> 00:19:14.660
And so that's really what
my first book became about.

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:19.520
Was really how was the story of
slavery and emancipation told

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:24.160
in the memorial landscape
after the Civil War.

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:30.160
And I, you know, I have
ancestors on both sides

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:33.450
of the war, but my father's
family was from Alabama.

00:19:33.450 --> 00:19:35.180
And with deep roots there.

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:38.730
And so that also partly drove
my interests, particularly

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:42.740
in the Confederate monuments and
trying to grapple, really reckon

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:46.720
in a serious way, with the
history of what I came to see

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:48.110
as a history of white supremacy

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:50.920
that lay behind the
Confederate memorials.

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:53.740
So you wanted me
to segue into-- .

