00:20:43.870 --> 00:20:45.170
&gt;&gt; Kirk Savage: Right.

00:20:45.170 --> 00:20:47.330
So you know, the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial really was a

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:49.170
game-changer, you
know, in the history

00:20:49.170 --> 00:20:51.510
of monuments in the
United States.

00:20:51.510 --> 00:20:54.730
And you know, my other panelists
can talk more about this.

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:57.260
But the, really the
public monument

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:59.780
as a form was more
abundant at the time

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:03.330
that that memorial was erected.

00:21:03.330 --> 00:21:06.730
And the incredible
outpouring of response to it,

00:21:06.730 --> 00:21:10.220
it's kind of immediate,
visceral success that it had,

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:15.440
really changed the
way everybody thought

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:17.780
about public monuments
at that time.

00:21:17.780 --> 00:21:20.830
It certainly drew in tons
of scholarly attention.

00:21:20.830 --> 00:21:23.280
But also tons of
popular attention to it.

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:26.640
And now all of a sudden, local
communities and other groups,

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:31.460
veterans groups, wanted to
build monuments as well.

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:36.230
And many of them following in
some way or another some formula

00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:39.080
that was pioneered by Maya Lin

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:41.770
in the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial.

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:45.430
And so that's what then really
has led to the transformation

00:21:45.430 --> 00:21:47.790
of the Mall in the late 20th
century with the addition

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:51.430
of the Korean War Memorial
and the World War II Memorial

00:21:51.430 --> 00:21:54.390
and now we have several
memorials authorized

00:21:54.390 --> 00:21:58.210
to even more recent
wars, the global war

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:00.250
on terror, for example.

00:22:00.250 --> 00:22:05.170
And just to put this in context,
there really was legislation,

00:22:05.170 --> 00:22:07.960
you know, after the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial was erected.

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:11.510
And kind of monuments
were now revived.

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:15.160
The congress began to
worry about the fact

00:22:15.160 --> 00:22:18.000
that there was a limited space
in the city, particularly

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.160
in the Mall area,
for new monuments.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.800
And so they adopted the
commemorative work sac,

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:24.100
which was supposed
to put the brakes

00:22:24.100 --> 00:22:26.930
on new memorial construction.

00:22:26.930 --> 00:22:30.150
And created certain
rules like a memorial

00:22:30.150 --> 00:22:34.170
to a person could only
be erected 25 years

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:35.720
after that person's death.

00:22:35.720 --> 00:22:39.150
A memorial to a war could
only be erected 10 years

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:42.300
after the declared
end of that war.

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:47.050
And that legislation of course
has been honored in the breach

00:22:47.050 --> 00:22:49.580
because many new
proposals have come forward

00:22:49.580 --> 00:22:52.550
which have gotten exemptions
from that legislation,

00:22:52.550 --> 00:22:55.770
like the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial education center.

00:22:55.770 --> 00:22:59.710
And now most recently the global
war on terror, which is a war

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:01.600
that is not only not over yet

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:06.250
but it's arguably never
going to be over in theory.

00:23:06.250 --> 00:23:10.790
So we have a situation now that
is really very, very different

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:13.400
from where we started with
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:15.620
in '82.

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:16.920
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Kristin?

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:18.220
&gt;&gt; Kristin Ann Hass:
I would add to that

00:23:18.220 --> 00:23:19.520
that in the United States,

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:22.630
there have been two
big memorial booms,

00:23:22.630 --> 00:23:26.700
two periods in which there was
intense interest in memory,

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:29.350
more broadly public
memory, more broadly,

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:31.460
and memorials in particular.

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:34.800
And the first, it's kind
of important to understand,

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:40.010
was in the period
from 1890 to 1920.

00:23:40.010 --> 00:23:44.430
And the memorials that were
built in that period were built,

00:23:44.430 --> 00:23:46.200
they were Civil War memorials.

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:49.800
But they came significantly
after the war.

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:52.690
And many of them were built
by women's organizations

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:55.960
on both sides, United
Daughters of the Confederacy,

00:23:55.960 --> 00:23:57.750
Daughters of the
American Revolution,

00:23:57.750 --> 00:24:00.460
all kinds of local
women's organizations

00:24:00.460 --> 00:24:05.410
and national women's
organizations really dedicated

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:10.550
to producing a very particular
memory of the Civil War.

00:24:10.550 --> 00:24:14.260
And after the first World
War and the second World War,

00:24:14.260 --> 00:24:19.860
there was very little interest
in monumentality in stone

00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:23.480
that would make a particular
meaning of those wars.

00:24:23.480 --> 00:24:28.440
Those wars were remembered by
small, local lists of names

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:31.930
in a town square, but
also really importantly,

00:24:31.930 --> 00:24:34.580
by infrastructure.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:37.960
Especially after the second
World War, World War II veterans

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:40.080
in their American
Legion meetings

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:42.920
and their local newspapers
were very explicit

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:45.880
that they wanted infrastructure.

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:48.330
My daughter, who's in the
second row, went through much

00:24:48.330 --> 00:24:50.910
of her life wearing a
t-shirt that said "Vets."

00:24:50.910 --> 00:24:53.900
Because she swam for the
Veterans Memorial swim team.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:55.630
Didn't really occur
to her necessarily

00:24:55.630 --> 00:25:00.160
that she was honoring the
service, the incredible service,

00:25:00.160 --> 00:25:02.380
of Americans during the
second World War, but in fact,

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:03.680
that's what they wanted.

00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:06.340
They wanted kids to have
pools and basketball courts

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:11.100
and it was Jan Scruggs and Maya
Lin's Vietnam Veterans Memorial

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:12.500
that changed that.

00:25:12.500 --> 00:25:15.320
That made memorials
mattered again

00:25:15.320 --> 00:25:17.960
and that inspired
this incredible,

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:21.330
short-term transformation
of the National Mall.

00:25:21.330 --> 00:25:26.460
And I spent a lot of time kind
of deep diving into the minutes

00:25:26.460 --> 00:25:28.260
of the meetings where
people argued

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:30.680
about the Korean War
Veterans Memorial,

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:33.580
the World War II
Memorial, the unbuilt

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:38.510
but completely fascinating
Black Revolutionary War

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:40.410
Patriots Memorial.

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:44.950
The Women's Memorial, women
in military service memorial,

00:25:44.950 --> 00:25:48.180
which fascinating, was kind
of paid for by the Saudis

00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:50.720
and the Kuwaitis, which
is super interesting.

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:55.720
And the National
Japanese American Memorial

00:25:55.720 --> 00:25:57.610
to patriotism during
World War II.

00:25:57.610 --> 00:26:02.070
So these memorials, built
in this period, entirely

00:26:02.070 --> 00:26:05.850
and explicitly both
inspired by the wall

00:26:05.850 --> 00:26:07.610
and in response to the wall.

00:26:07.610 --> 00:26:12.940
And in the case of two big
and most successful memorials,

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:14.620
the Second World War memorial

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:18.270
and the Korean War Veterans
Memorial, corrective.

00:26:18.270 --> 00:26:20.920
Explicitly corrective.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:25.870
We are going to fix what's
wrong with the Vietnam Memorial,

00:26:25.870 --> 00:26:27.830
what's wrong with the
Vietnam Memorial in the view

00:26:27.830 --> 00:26:30.820
of the people who wanted to
build these other memorials was

00:26:30.820 --> 00:26:33.300
that these same eighth
graders who were going

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:36.430
through the National Museum of
American History were coming

00:26:36.430 --> 00:26:40.690
to the Mall to this important
side of national pilgrimage,

00:26:40.690 --> 00:26:45.950
and learning that dying in an
American War could be tragic.

00:26:45.950 --> 00:26:48.160
And wasn't necessarily heroic.

00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:54.270
And in an era of
all-volunteer military, tricky.

00:26:54.270 --> 00:26:57.450
And so those memorials
were built in response.

