00:27:26.940 --> 00:27:28.880
So please take-- .

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:31.890
&gt;&gt; James Reston Jr: So if
you have a look at "A Rift

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:36.560
in the Earth," you'll see that
I have a color section in there

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:41.200
of the [inaudible] of other
concepts by other artists

00:27:41.200 --> 00:27:44.300
for a Vietnam memorial.

00:27:44.300 --> 00:27:49.290
And you see in those [inaudible]
the struggle that artists went

00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:53.240
through to try to conceptualize
what would be appropriate

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:55.820
for a lost war.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:28:01.770
And nobody can look at
those other examples

00:28:01.770 --> 00:28:06.050
without thinking
how lucky we were

00:28:06.050 --> 00:28:11.040
that Maya Lin had her
concept for this thing.

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:16.100
One of the things that
interests me immensely

00:28:16.100 --> 00:28:21.050
about the Vietnam Memorial
today is the evolution

00:28:21.050 --> 00:28:23.760
of it since it was built.

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:29.740
In my view, it is no
longer a veterans memorial.

00:28:29.740 --> 00:28:31.480
It's become globalized.

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:34.010
It's become internationalized.

00:28:34.010 --> 00:28:36.440
As a memorial for everyone.

00:28:36.440 --> 00:28:40.510
At the beginning, it was
as if the veterans had,

00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:43.440
it was their proprietary
memorial.

00:28:43.440 --> 00:28:45.700
And it was just for them.

00:28:45.700 --> 00:28:50.540
But as time has gone
on, it's changed

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:53.750
and it's become important
to everybody.

00:28:53.750 --> 00:28:57.780
It's also in a way no
longer about Vietnam.

00:28:57.780 --> 00:29:04.600
It's become internationalized
and made universal.

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:08.790
Universalized I should
say, as a comment,

00:29:08.790 --> 00:29:11.780
a commentary on all wars.

00:29:11.780 --> 00:29:17.430
The Vietnam memorial is
about the cost of war.

00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:19.720
And that's universal.

00:29:19.720 --> 00:29:21.440
That's a universal theme.

00:29:21.440 --> 00:29:27.820
And it's one that will make
that memorial live forever.

00:29:27.820 --> 00:29:32.230
It's also, as they've
said, been a game-changer

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:34.710
for belonged of all
war memorials.

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:37.810
For example, when
I went to Vietnam,

00:29:37.810 --> 00:29:45.300
there is a memorial north of
the DMZ which is a memorial

00:29:45.300 --> 00:29:49.530
for the dead of the north
Vietnamese in Vietnam.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:52.900
And how do they memorialize
that?

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:59.700
By black granite slabs with the
names of the dead in Vietnamese.

00:29:59.700 --> 00:30:03.550
So that's an example
of how, what the impact

00:30:03.550 --> 00:30:09.490
of this artistic concept
of remembering war not

00:30:09.490 --> 00:30:12.840
for its glory and its
service necessarily,

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:20.350
but simply for the cost and
the carnage of warfare itself.

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:24.470
The whole thing about
the evolution

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:31.100
of Civil War memorials is also
a theme here it seems to me.

00:30:31.100 --> 00:30:35.040
That when I was a
student at Chapel Hill

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:37.280
and a professor there
for 10 years,

00:30:37.280 --> 00:30:42.480
the Silent Sam statue
was a joke figure.

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:47.550
It was this sort of
generic, interesting statue

00:30:47.550 --> 00:30:49.800
with a soldier holding a gun.

00:30:49.800 --> 00:30:54.280
And he was Silent Sam because
he shot his gun off whenever a

00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:58.730
virgin walked by.

00:30:58.730 --> 00:31:04.220
That joke is actually not
unique to Chapel Hill.

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:06.570
My daughter, for
example, went to Cornell,

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:12.790
and on the Cornell campus, there
are statues of the two founders

00:31:12.790 --> 00:31:15.910
that face one another
and there are footsteps

00:31:15.910 --> 00:31:17.580
in between the two statues.

00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:21.330
And the notion is that
whenever a virgin walked by,

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:24.740
the two statues,
statuary figures got up

00:31:24.740 --> 00:31:28.130
and met one another in the
middle and shook hands.

00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:33.100
So Silent Sam was
a totally benign,

00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:37.510
uninteresting, forgotten piece.

00:31:37.510 --> 00:31:43.270
And suddenly by honestly
some very fine scholarship,

00:31:43.270 --> 00:31:50.160
this 1913 dedication of
the statue was discovered

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:58.050
in all its horror and scurrilous
white supremacist rhetoric.

00:31:58.050 --> 00:32:07.040
And so suddenly, Silent Sam
takes life as a very vibrant,

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:13.690
passionate and scurrilous
symbol of white racism.

00:32:14.770 --> 00:32:19.450
And what do we do about
this sort of thing?

00:32:19.450 --> 00:32:22.790
I've heard it said what needs
to happen in the South is

00:32:22.790 --> 00:32:28.470
that there be a movement in
which all of the South is swept.

00:32:28.470 --> 00:32:33.510
Every small town that
has a Confederate soldier

00:32:33.510 --> 00:32:38.760
on a pedestal needs to be
swept and these statues taken

00:32:38.760 --> 00:32:41.920
down in one way or another.

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:44.940
I'm very concerned
with the way in which

00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:51.690
that Silent Sam statue was
torn down and destroyed.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:56.760
It concerns me as a historian
about what is the impact

00:32:56.760 --> 00:33:00.440
of that kind of action
and where does it lead?

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:03.830
Is this basically leading
us towards a concept

00:33:03.830 --> 00:33:10.130
of the Civil War of glory on the
northern side and humiliation

00:33:10.130 --> 00:33:14.180
and shame on the confederate
side and therefore any symbol

00:33:14.180 --> 00:33:17.950
of the Southern Confederacy
is shameful?

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:23.180
This leads to book burnings.

00:33:23.180 --> 00:33:30.080
And I'm, and a, from the
sanitizing, white-washing

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:35.450
of history, it leads to, in
my view, a very one-sided,

00:33:35.450 --> 00:33:39.140
one-minded way of
looking at history.

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:42.020
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Kirk,
you want to add anything?

00:33:42.020 --> 00:33:45.780
You've written, and I was
interested in your book,

00:33:45.780 --> 00:33:49.210
which has a long section
on monument avenue

00:33:49.210 --> 00:33:52.200
and the Lee Memorial
in Richmond.

00:33:52.200 --> 00:33:57.170
And I recommend to the
audience to look at the mayor

00:33:57.170 --> 00:34:00.830
of Richmond commissioned
a very thoughtful process

00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:05.530
to evaluate what to do with
monument avenue and it's online

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:08.900
on the City of Richmond's
website.

00:34:08.900 --> 00:34:11.040
But I'd like you,
I'm sure you've read

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:12.430
that and looked at-- .

00:34:12.430 --> 00:34:13.730
&gt;&gt; Kirk Savage: Yeah.

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:15.030
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: And
offer your observations

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:16.330
in light of what Jim has said.

00:34:16.330 --> 00:34:17.630
&gt;&gt; Kirk Savage.

00:34:17.630 --> 00:34:19.300
Sure, well this is
a very vexed issue.

00:34:19.300 --> 00:34:20.880
I think Jim and I have maybe,

00:34:20.880 --> 00:34:23.230
are maybe on somewhat
different ends

00:34:23.230 --> 00:34:25.220
of the spectrum on
this question.

00:34:25.220 --> 00:34:28.510
As an art historian,
of course I'm inclined

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:29.990
for its preservation.

00:34:29.990 --> 00:34:33.650
If stuff isn't preserved,
we can't study it.

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:36.990
So that's a basic
kind of bottom line.

00:34:36.990 --> 00:34:41.560
The problem is these monuments
that are out in public space

00:34:41.560 --> 00:34:43.320
that are honored,
they're honored by virtue

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:46.470
of where they are, they were
put up for particular reasons

00:34:46.470 --> 00:34:50.410
to actually advance
certain agendas.

00:34:50.410 --> 00:34:52.340
And how do we reckon with that

00:34:52.340 --> 00:34:55.810
and how do we contest those
agendas now in the present?

00:34:55.810 --> 00:34:57.110
What's the right thing to do?

00:34:57.110 --> 00:35:01.540
There really aren't a lot
of easy answers to that.

00:35:01.540 --> 00:35:06.570
My view is that the monuments
themselves sanitize history.

00:35:06.570 --> 00:35:08.780
They tell a particular
version of history.

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:12.280
They were motivated
by white supremacy.

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:16.710
And they were meant to
actually celebrate the triumph

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:19.260
of white supremacy in the South.

00:35:19.260 --> 00:35:23.000
And that is a very
difficult pill to swallow now.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.080
So I mean I can just
tell you from my own,

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:26.870
my personal experience
in Pittsburgh,

00:35:26.870 --> 00:35:30.510
we had a monument
erected to Stephen Foster,

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:34.980
which featured a black,
a barefoot, black,

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:39.690
toothless black banjo
player sitting at his feet.

00:35:39.690 --> 00:35:44.080
And for a long time, it was also
kind of like Silent Sam, a joke,

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:47.650
at least within the sort of
white professoriate, like me,

00:35:47.650 --> 00:35:49.110
it was kind of a joke.

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:53.580
But once Charlottesville
happened and those people

00:35:53.580 --> 00:35:54.880
in the public sphere,

00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:56.550
particularly the African
American community,

00:35:56.550 --> 00:36:01.440
felt more empowered to actually
speak up about this statue,

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:06.050
we you know, saw how long
they had been living painfully

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:07.350
with this monument.

00:36:07.350 --> 00:36:10.720
For so many years and had
their voices, in fact,

00:36:10.720 --> 00:36:12.360
they had protested it
at different times,

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:15.080
but their voices had been
for the most part ignored.

00:36:15.080 --> 00:36:18.430
Has to be remembered that public
space is not a level playing

00:36:18.430 --> 00:36:21.730
field where everybody
has free speech.

00:36:21.730 --> 00:36:25.650
So public monuments
were erected by people

00:36:25.650 --> 00:36:28.230
who had the power to erect them.

00:36:28.230 --> 00:36:30.190
And that power continues.

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:34.000
And so that is the problem
that we, I think, face today.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.900
And it has changed my thinking.

00:36:36.900 --> 00:36:38.430
I mean I see a whole range

00:36:38.430 --> 00:36:41.690
of solutions possible
for monuments.

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:43.750
But none of them are easy.

00:36:43.750 --> 00:36:45.750
And none of them are cost-free.

00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:49.380
And I do see removal
is one option.

00:36:49.380 --> 00:36:50.680
That's in fact what happened

00:36:50.680 --> 00:36:53.800
to my Stephen Foster
statue, is it's gone now.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:55.100
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Right.

