00:40:24.250 --> 00:40:27.060
and President Obama designated
The Bears Ears National Monument

00:40:27.060 --> 00:40:28.360
in Utah.

00:40:28.360 --> 00:40:31.130
The first one to be co-managed
by Native American peoples

00:40:31.130 --> 00:40:32.460
and the US Government.

00:40:32.460 --> 00:40:34.680
And the current administration
has shrunken the size

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:35.980
of both of those monuments.

00:40:35.980 --> 00:40:38.660
And I wonder, my question
is, what does that say

00:40:38.660 --> 00:40:40.440
about changing values
in America?

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:43.850
And what is the larger
statement about tearing

00:40:43.850 --> 00:40:47.130
down these structures say
about our values as a country?

00:40:47.130 --> 00:40:48.660
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Thank you.

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:52.290
Jim, you want to tackle that?

00:40:52.290 --> 00:40:54.160
&gt;&gt; James Reston Jr: Well,
we had a telephone call.

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:57.310
The three of us, the four
of us, about this thing.

00:40:57.310 --> 00:41:04.570
And the concept arose
called presentism.

00:41:04.570 --> 00:41:08.420
And the definition of
presentism is the application

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:13.480
of values today on past events.

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:19.000
It's a very I think
useful concept for analysis

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.830
of the Civil War memorial theme.

00:41:21.830 --> 00:41:23.790
Because it raises the question

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:28.310
of how are our values today
playing into how we look

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:31.930
at memorials that were
established long ago?

00:41:31.930 --> 00:41:39.240
And in the case of Silent
Sam at UNC, is it really fair

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:48.840
to impose our values
today on a generic statue

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:53.760
of a Civil War soldier?

00:41:55.260 --> 00:42:06.560
You know, that memorial
was so benign for so long,

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:10.430
without any of this thing.

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:17.410
So suddenly we are meant to
feel what people felt in 1913

00:42:17.410 --> 00:42:19.750
in relation to our values.

00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:21.180
It should be remembered

00:42:21.180 --> 00:42:27.350
that 483,000 Southern
men were casualties

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:29.760
of the American Civil War.

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:34.710
And so is at least
a part of the way

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:38.410
in which these statues
were erected.

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:41.410
And this is where Kirk and
I would have our debate.

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:46.050
That those statues were
partly erected for the grief

00:42:46.050 --> 00:42:49.430
of the loss of Southern boys.

00:42:49.430 --> 00:42:54.750
And perhaps secondarily for
the whole process of invasion.

00:42:54.750 --> 00:42:57.920
Not necessarily for the
protection of slavery.

00:42:57.920 --> 00:43:02.790
But the invasion of
the South by the North.

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:06.670
So I think it's not a
complete explanation

00:43:06.670 --> 00:43:12.050
to just cast upon all of these
statues that were erected on,

00:43:12.050 --> 00:43:18.480
about the confederacy in
relation to our values today.

