a response

00:45:56.250 --> 00:45:58.540
to the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial,

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:01.060
it was intended as a corrective.

00:46:01.060 --> 00:46:05.330
It was intended to
be heroic, masculine.

00:46:05.330 --> 00:46:08.080
And celebratory in the ways

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:11.560
that the Vietnam War Memorial
was not perceived to be.

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:16.390
The biggest, there were
many debates and fights.

00:46:16.390 --> 00:46:19.430
The most intense was about race.

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:20.940
Everywhere you look,
doesn't matter

00:46:20.940 --> 00:46:23.120
if the war memorial doesn't
seem like it's going to be

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:25.300
about race, it ends
up being about race.

00:46:25.300 --> 00:46:29.590
The original design had
38 all white figures.

00:46:29.590 --> 00:46:34.180
Which you know, turned
out to be a problem.

00:46:34.180 --> 00:46:37.850
And then there was
intense debate about which

00:46:37.850 --> 00:46:42.470
of the 19 figures in the
final design would be raced

00:46:42.470 --> 00:46:43.770
in what way.

00:46:43.770 --> 00:46:46.710
And when I talked to the
sculptor, Frank Gaylord

00:46:46.710 --> 00:46:48.080
on the telephone, one

00:46:48.080 --> 00:46:49.990
of the very first things
he said I asked him

00:46:49.990 --> 00:46:52.840
about the first figure, and he
said "God damn it, he's white.

00:46:52.840 --> 00:46:55.290
He has a broad nose,
but he's white.

00:46:55.290 --> 00:46:58.110
I'm white, and I
have a broad nose."

00:46:58.110 --> 00:47:02.950
So there was intense debate
about how big their lips were,

00:47:02.950 --> 00:47:06.270
whether or not that made
them look lazy, about whether

00:47:06.270 --> 00:47:08.420
or not they had limp wrists.

00:47:08.420 --> 00:47:13.540
So that's a very short answer
to a super interesting question.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:14.840
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:14.840 --> 00:47:16.730
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: I think we're
going to have the last question?

00:47:16.730 --> 00:47:18.330
Oh, two minutes, okay, good.

00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:21.430
&gt;&gt; I have the shortest
question for Mr. Savage

00:47:21.430 --> 00:47:25.280
for the Lincoln Memorial
on the National Mall,

00:47:25.280 --> 00:47:28.660
the Emancipation
Proclamation is omitted.

00:47:28.660 --> 00:47:29.960
Should it be there?

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:33.680
And was it omitted
accidently or deliberately?

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:35.010
&gt;&gt; Kirk Savage: Well
I'd say deliberately.

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:40.250
Because the idea behind
the inscriptions was to try

00:47:40.250 --> 00:47:42.620
to avoid the issue of slavery.

00:47:42.620 --> 00:47:47.640
And to turn Lincoln from
the Emancipator figure

00:47:47.640 --> 00:47:50.770
that he had been to
more of a reunifier.

00:47:50.770 --> 00:47:52.910
So that's why they chose
the Gettysburg Address

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:54.530
and the second inaugural.

00:47:54.530 --> 00:47:56.940
Of course, though, the problem
is the second inaugural has this

00:47:56.940 --> 00:48:00.230
incredible line about slavery
and about how the war was

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:02.350
about slavery and
it's our punishment

00:48:02.350 --> 00:48:04.150
for the crime of slavery.

00:48:04.150 --> 00:48:07.200
It's really the only place
in the memorial landscape

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:10.500
of Washington that really
talks about the crime,

00:48:10.500 --> 00:48:13.390
the historical crime of slavery.

00:48:13.390 --> 00:48:15.610
So it's a mixed bat.

00:48:15.610 --> 00:48:16.910
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass:
I encourage you

00:48:16.910 --> 00:48:19.460
to go read the second inaugural
at the Lincoln Memorial.

00:48:19.460 --> 00:48:20.760
Of course you can look it up,

00:48:20.760 --> 00:48:22.860
but it's more powerful
reading it there.

00:48:22.860 --> 00:48:25.310
And then the Gettysburg
Address calling for a new birth

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:28.920
of freedom I think suggests
what the war was all about.

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:32.820
One more question, wrap it up.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:34.120
Sure, Jim.

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:35.950
&gt;&gt; James Reston Jr: Well what
we haven't had time to talk

00:48:35.950 --> 00:48:37.250
about is this whole thing

00:48:37.250 --> 00:48:43.050
of contextualizing the
Civil War memorials.

00:48:43.050 --> 00:48:48.060
And there's a very interesting
effort to do that in Richmond.

00:48:48.060 --> 00:48:54.090
And right after 2000, a
Lincoln Memorial was built to go

00:48:54.090 --> 00:48:58.050
in front of the Civil
War museum in Richmond.

00:48:58.050 --> 00:49:04.180
It's a lovely statue with
Lincoln and his son, Ted,

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:08.750
who visited Richmond when it was
still smoldering at the very end

00:49:08.750 --> 00:49:11.310
of the Civil War, he
was very much open

00:49:11.310 --> 00:49:13.310
to assassination there.

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:15.280
So that is meant
to be a counterpart

00:49:15.280 --> 00:49:19.140
to the monument boulevard thing.

00:49:19.140 --> 00:49:21.940
But does that really
contextualize

00:49:21.940 --> 00:49:23.870
monument boulevard?

00:49:23.870 --> 00:49:25.310
I don't think so.

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:27.470
&gt;&gt; Brent D. Glass: Our
authors will be around all day.

00:49:27.470 --> 00:49:29.260
Please give them a
round of applause

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:31.060
for a wonderful [inaudible].

